T1  - Net value: wealth creation (and destruction) during the internet boom
AU  - Hendershott, Robert J.
JO  - Journal of Corporate Finance
VL  - 10
IS  - 2
SP  - 281
EP  - 299
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/03/01/
T2  - Venture Capital, Initial Public Offerings, and Entrepreneurial Finance
SN  - 0929-1199
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0929-1199(03)00058-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0929119903000580
KW  - Internet
KW  - Wealth creation
KW  - Venture capital
AB  - During the internet bubble, dot-com stocks rose by a factor of 35, creating what we now know were massively distorted price signals. This paper looks at net value creation in a sample of 441 venture-backed dot-coms that received over US$21 billion from private and public equity investors. As of the end of 2001, this US$21 billion corresponded to an estimated US$39 billion of enterprise value, giving an annualized return-on-equity capital invested of 19%. These results suggest that, despite the distorted price signals and contrary to popular perception, wealth was created during the dot-com investment boom.
ER  - 
